  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency WASH response for new arrivals in MMC and Jere LGAs</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Close to 8.5 million people are affected by the current conflict/ or violence in north-east Nigeria caused by Armed Opposition Groups (AOG) related violence since 2009. According to HRP, 25,261 persons have been displaced from Guzamala, Monguno, Magumeri, Ngala, Gwoza and Kukawa LGAs of Borno State, Nigeria to Maiduguri Metropolitan Centre (MMC) Local Government Area (LGA) since November 2018.Of those 25,621 IDPs, 4845 people are in Bayain Taxaco Informal Camp, while 2,500 are staying in groups of 15-20 households amongst the host communities but are not fully integrated into the host community. At the moment there are no WaSH partners operating in Bayain Taxaco despite extreme WaSH needs revealed during Solidarites needs assessments and UNICEF&#x2019;s WaSH gap analysis. Moreover, data shared by UNICEF in February 2019 show important gaps in sanitation facilities and water access across Borno State, specifically 22 sites in Jere and MMC LGAs.

Solidarites International (Solidarites) is thus proposing to:
I. Provide lifesaving WaSH support to IDPs in Bayain Taxaco Informal Camp in terms of access to water. Indeed, access to sanitation is to be covered by an ECHO grant for this camp in 2019
II. Support emergency construction of sanitation facilities in sites where gaps have been identified as the greatest by the WASH Sector in Maiduguri and Jere LGAs. This will complement SI&#x2019;s water trucking capacity to be covered by another ECHO grant for Maiduguri. This capacity will be to cater for the needs of 3,500 people for a duration of 3 months.

In total, the proposed project is targeting 10,848 individuals.</narrative>
  </description>
